{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17636093","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17636093"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T18:23:29+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T18:23:29+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17562"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17562","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17562"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.84,0.1,0.06,0,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10252"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78221"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10252","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10252"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17562"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63630"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"7185"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23960"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24154"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78221","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/78221"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe trigeminal nerve is the fifth cranial nerve and emerges from the lateral aspect of the pons.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the function of the trigeminal nerve?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Sensory to face and motor to muscles of mastication","Sensory to face and motor to muscles of facial expression","Motor to facial muscles and taste to anterior two-thirds of tongue","Motor to extraocular muscles and sensory to cornea","Sensory to posterior tongue and motor to pharyngeal muscles"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe trigeminal nerve (cranial nerve V) provides \u003Cstrong\u003Esensory to face and motor to muscles of mastication\u003C/strong\u003E. It has three main branches:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003EOphthalmic (V1): purely sensory to upper face, forehead, and eye\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EMaxillary (V2): purely sensory to midface and upper teeth\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EMandibular (V3): mixed sensory and motor - sensory to lower face, anterior tongue and lower teeth; motor to muscles of mastication\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe muscles of mastication include:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003ETemporalis\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EMasseter\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EMedial and lateral pterygoids\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe other options describe different cranial nerves:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESensory to face and motor to muscles of facial expression\u003C/strong\u003E - Facial nerve (CN VII)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMotor to facial muscles and taste to anterior two-thirds of tongue\u003C/strong\u003E - Also facial nerve (CN VII)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMotor to extraocular muscles and sensory to cornea\u003C/strong\u003E - A combination of oculomotor (CN III), trochlear (CN IV), and abducens (CN VI) nerves\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESensory to posterior tongue and motor to pharyngeal muscles\u003C/strong\u003E - Glossopharyngeal nerve (CN IX)\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe trigeminal nerve is the largest cranial nerve. Its sensory component transmits touch, pain, temperature and proprioception from the face, while its motor component controls chewing movements.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The trigeminal nerve (CN V) has three major branches: ophthalmic (V1), maxillary (V2), and mandibular (V3)","The trigeminal nerve provides sensory innervation to the face and motor innervation to the muscles of mastication","The trigeminal nerve emerges from the pons, not above it"],"references":["Netter FH. Netter Atlas of Human Anatomy: A Regional Approach with Latin Terminology. Eighth edition. Elsevier; 2022."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63630"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17562"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63630","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/63630"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-09T21:36:45+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-09T21:37:37+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10252"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78221"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0